On Spring Break this week but really wanted to share this. April and May are fantastic times to add a new dog to the family. Please consider rescue. Some animals that end up in shelters carry no wounds, some look like this just on the outside, some just on the inside, and some are both emotionally and physically wounded - all by no fault of their own. The goal of an adopter is to realize this, determine what healing needs to happen and slowly and compassionately address each cut and tear. There is no better feeling than watching a helpless animal in your care build themselves back up. As a parent this is a priceless lesson you can teach your children. As the leader in your family, you can pay tutors, put your kids on teams, tell them stories of the bravery and courage of others, but the lessons learned through rescue cannot be bought or told. The lessons learned through rescue build better humans and in turn the society so many are clamoring for. Just food for thought. #adoptdontshop

Even for the most conservative guests, I push for a skin taper in the nape for a number of reasons. A skin taper removes the unwanted length at the lower neck while eliminating the need for a lineup on the bottom hairline. I've always felt that a stamped-in hairline tends to look too artificial and appears like a line of demarcation in the next couple of weeks as the hair grows out. A skin taper solves this issue by not leaving a line to begin with, allowing the hairs at the nape to grow out as evenly as possible. Some guests may resist this idea, as they may be comfortable with the type of cut they have been getting. But it's important to introduce new concepts and aesthetics to clients as it gives them the option of staying modern and relevant. ___ Tag someone who you would like to introduce this to!  Î”

James Billington (1847 - December 13, 1901) was an executioner of England from 1884 to 1901. He was born in Preston, Lancashire. Billington had a "lifelong fascination" with hanging, and made replica gallows in his back yard on which he practiced with weights and dummies and, it was rumored locally, stray dogs and cats. After the death of William Marwood in 1883, the position opened up for a new Executioner of the City of London. Billington was 1 of the 3 on the shortlist to be the next executioner but the job was given to Bartholomew Binns. Billington wrote letters to English authorities offering to be a hangman and he was accepted by the authorities in Yorkshire. Billington's first execution was Joseph Laycock at Armley Gaol in Leeds, on August 26, 1884. Laylock was convicted of murdering his wife and 4 children. In 1891, Billington became the Chief Executioner over Great Britain and Ireland. Billington executed serial poisoner Thomas Neill Cream on November 15, 1892. Billington claimed Cream's last words were "I am Jack" implying he was Jack the Ripper but Cream was in Chicago at the time of the Ripper murders. Billington's final execution was Patrick McKenna on November 13, 1901 after McKenna was sentenced to hanging for the murder of his wife with a razor while in a rage for not giving him money to buy beer. #1800s #19century #history #execution #death #hang #hangman #jobs #England #Ireland #GreatBritain #Preston #Lancashire #Yorkshire #gallows #trapdoor #London #city #murder #razors #money #beer #cream #jack #Chicago #police #jail #wife #children #trial

At one time Gormully & Jeffrey were the 2nd largest bicycle manufacturers in the country! Interested in knowing more about 213's past? Take a walk through our North stairwell! Frankie Yale was a young kid when his life of crime would get started. A friend of Johnny Torri he would find himself in the Five Points Gang in New York. A dozen murders by 21 Yale was a tough no nonsense gangster. With the move of Torrio to Chicago Yale would find himself in charge of almost all the rackets in the gang which included Extortion,Brothels, protection. With money made from the rackets Yale would buy a bar know as the Harvard Inn in Coney Island and employed  by Yale was a young man named Al Capone. Its the Harvard Inn where Capone earned his name scarface in a fight. Durning the beginning of prohibition Torrio wanted to expanded Jim Colosimos business to include illegal alcohol not wanting to expand Torrio would bring to Chicago Yale to eliminate Colosimo. With prohibition in full effect most illegal alcohol was coming from the Unione Siciliane where it was rumored that Yale was the president. After the retirement of Torrio a new Boss of The Outfit would emerge his name Capone. Capone would get alcohol from Yale which was ship from Brooklyn to Chicago. After many of Capone shipments were hijacked  never making it to Chicago Capone felt something was up and he was right. Sending a friend to spy on Yale James DeAmato was able to confimn the suspicious of Capone. Yale was hijacking his own shipments and reselling them to Capone. With this act of betrayal and Yale trying to take over parts of Capone area a contact was put out. On July 1st, 1928 Yales was driving and forced into a curb by another car. A barrage of bullets flew from the car and riddle Yales body. Its said that one of the guns recovered was a Tommy Gun the first time it had been used in a New York killing. Salvatore Capone, better known as Frank was the elder brother of Chicago Outfit boss Alphonse Capone. Growing up in New York, both Frank and Al became involved in the infamous "Five Points Gang" with mobster John Torrio. By 1918, Torrio had moved to Chicago to help a relative defend his rackets, and Torrio soon asked Al and later Frank to join him there. Frank, a man who experts say could have written an even bloodier chapter in American crime than his infamous brother had a dedication to bloodletting and more savage instincts than Al. Al always exercised a certain patience. His credo, absorbed from the teachings of Johnny Torrio, was â€œalways try to deal before you have to kill.â€ Frank's observation was, "You never get no back talk from no corpse.â€ He died at the age 29 after being shot by police during the Capones take over of Cicero in 1924. #SalvatoreCapone #FrankCapone #ChocagoOutfit #ChicagoMob #Chicago #Cicero

In honor of the #Cubs home opener tonight, here's a throwback from last year freezing my butt off in the bleachers with some of my favorite people.

#shutdownchicagoslaughterhouses  There is a great injustice happening at Park Packing Co and every other slaughterhouse in this city and beyond. We came to stop this truck because every animal trapped inside does not deserve to die. Every lamb and piglet we met is someone's daughter, son, sister, or brother. Every lamb and piglet is someone.  These animals are not disposable objects for human pleasure. They are not things, they are animals and they are people. Just like us.  As activists it is our duty to speak out against this horrible atrocity, to directly confront the violence. This atrocity happens in the dead of night because it's too shameful for the public to witness or know about.  We bared witness today to offer comfort and kindness to those who have never known either. Not from humans. They receive comfort from one another and only for a few brief minutes from us today in the moments before they were killed.  Right now, everyone who they've ever known will die with them inside that slaughterhouse. They must watch their loved ones be butchered before their very eyes. How is this okay? How is this humane?  There is no humane way to kill someone who does not want to die. There is no way to exploit someone and call it humane. It's not food, it's violence.  More photos and vids coming. Thanks all for being brave and bearing witness to this atrocity today.

Who's your MVP? The Beard or The Brodie? Now there's a huge MVP rivalry between the two. Both players are triple double machines and both are very dominant. Now I personally think Harden should win MVP just by a tiny bit and I'll explain why. Harden came from a sixth man to an All-Star and MVP candidate. Harden led his team from 8th seed in the west to the 3rd seed in the west. While on the other hand, Russ is just averaging triple doubles and scoring them every night. Now both of their teams' are in the playoff spots right now. And Harden did prove a point saying that he thought that being MVP is about winning. And I do agree on what he's saying. For example, let's take it back to 2011. Rose was a MVP candidate and lead his team to 62-20 record with his team being the best team in the league. Rose averaging great stats and having the best record is a little equivalent to Harden almost averaging a triple double (just by two rebounds off) and having the third best team in the league. So I personally believe Harden should win. Russell Westbrook is a great player and is the best PG out there. Russ does deserve to win MVP. But I believe that winning is a big essential into being placed in the MVP spot. So my vote goes to James Harden. Now a lot of you guys or most of you guys may disagree. But again both players have their pros and cons and possibly or most likely Russell Westbrook might win due to his dominance. So my vote goes to Harden. I have nothing against Russ, but I'm just stating my opinion. You guys may comment your opinion down below if you may like to. If you guys go look at the MVP ladder by week, you'll see that Harden and Westbrook just go back and forth at it. Cheers to the best week of the year!! I'm so pumped for Good Friday and Easter, the entire atmosphere is filled with the Spirit more than any other time in my opinion! For me-Christs death and resurrection is more important than his birth. The bell tower of St. James Cathedral, located at 65 E Huron Street in the Gold Coast Neighborhood of Chicago, IL. The church was originally designed in 1855, but most of it was ruined during the Great Chicago Fire of 1871.  The bell tower, however, survived the Great Fire, and thus, is older than the rest of the current Cathedral.  It is charred at the top, partly because of the fire, but also perhaps because of the ravages of the industrial revolution.  It shows the Gothic revival architecture of the time, with the pointed arches of the windows, and it is made out of Athens Marble (like the Water Tower and Holy Name Cathedral). #digitalchicago #relg320 #LFC #sociology #anthropology #archaeology #architecture #gothic #chicago #religion #cathedral #episcopal #tower #industry #culture #material #marble #urban

At UJI, another secret spot for the best Cherry Blossom watching. There are about 2.000 Sakura trees at the Byodoin Garden and along the Uji Riverside.  Uji (å®‡æ²») is a small city situated between Kyoto and Nara, two of Japan's most famous historical and cultural centers. Its proximity to these two former capitals resulted in Uji's early development as a cultural center in its own right. At the height of political power of the Fujiwara clan in the Heian Period (794 to 1192), buildings such as Byodoin Temple and Ujigami Shrine, the oldest extant shrine in Japan, were contructed in Uji. Uji is also famous for its green tea.  There are 2 top attractions here are Byodoin Temple and Uji River.  Byodoin Temple is a striking example of Buddhist Pure Land (Jodo) architecture. Together with its garden, the temple represents the Pure Land Paradise and was influential on later temple construction. Byodoin was initially built in 998 as a countryside retreat villa for the powerful politician Fujiwara no Michinaga, not as a temple. Uji river is famous its birds fish catching attractions. Visitors can sail along the river enjoying the scenery of the riversides.  There a lot of small restaurants, tea house and greentea dessert cafe.  Most of the visitors here are local Japanese, not crowded at all and you can enjoy a relax moment here watching the beautiful cherry blossom.  Uji, Japan

Pierre-August Renoir, French (1841-1919), 'Luncheon of the Boating Party' 1880-1881. This painting captures the atmosphere as Renoir's friends shared food & drinks on the balcony overlooking the Seine River at the Maison Fournaise Restaurant in Chatou. This was a popular gathering place for Parisians to rent rowing skiffs, eat & drink, and spend the evening. Renoir composed this scene over many months, painting the individual figures when the models (his friends) were available, & adding the stripped awning along the top edge. The painting has numerous popular culture references. Jean-Pierre Jeunet's film 'Amelie' is one prominent reference, with the woman right of center (Amelie?) sipping a glass, gazing uninterested as everyone around her is engaged & enjoying the day. The painting is also referenced in Susan Vreelands 2007 novel with the same name. At the 7th Impressionist Exhibit in 1882, it received wide praise as one of the best things Renoir had painted. 19-month-old Syrian refugee Sham Haj Khalad wears her grandfather's glasses at her home Friday, April 14, 2017, in Skokie, Ill. Fleeing the civil war in Syria, Sham's grandfather Khaled Haj Khalaf and his wife, Fattoum Bakir, came to Chicago in September 2016 with three of their children, but their oldest daughter Baraa Haj Khalaf and her family were denied entry in January of this year after President Donald Trump's immigration order banning all immigrants from Syria. Baraa, her husband Abdulmajeed and Sham spent two years in a Turkish refugee camp for the proper paperwork, interviews and background checks required to come to America. They were all finally reunited in February and now live together in the same apartment building.
